Integration tests that wire up a full Mesh node similar to the wired tests in mesh-grpc, but
        also spin up a cluster of Mesh nodes that act as replicas. This allows for tests to be written
        from the perspective of one node that verify that replication and repair works as expected.
        These wired tests make it much easier to bring the local node into an 'out-of-sync' state
        which is useful when testing replication/repair. Wired tests also have access to
        GitProcessBuilderFactory and @Repo to more easily set up test data.

        The module was created to avoid having to copy implementations of features that need to be supported for
        both Mesh and the 'classic' git implementation in Bitbucket Server to support mixed mode (where BBS uses
        the classic SCM for local repositories, and Mesh for remote repositories.

        Once the classic SCM support is removed from Bitbucket Server, this module should be deleted and its contents
        merged into mesh-common.

This pom is intended to be used by plugins which are built outside of the scope of the main Confluence project.
        It acts as a way of managing the dependencies of those plugins so that they match the Confluence version.

        It means that the plugins no longer have to manually specify the version of stuff like atlassian-rest-common
        so that it matches the Confluence version, they can just inherit the managed version.

        e.g.

        
        <dependencyManagement>
            <dependencies>
                <dependency>
                    <groupId>com.atlassian.confluence</groupId>
                    <artifactId>confluence-plugins-platform-pom</artifactId>
                    <version>${confluence.version}</version>
                    <type>pom</type>
                    <scope>import</scope>
                </dependency>
            </dependencies>
        </dependencyManagement>

This pom is a cousin of confluence-plugins-platform-pom. It is intended to be used by plugins which are built
        outside of the scope of the main Confluence project. It acts as a way of managing the dependencies of test
        libraries for those plugins so that they match the Confluence version.

        It means that the plugins no longer have to manually specify the version of stuff like htmlunit, selenium and
        confluence-stateless-test-runner

        e.g.

        
        <dependencyManagement>
            <dependencies>
                <dependency>
                    <groupId>com.atlassian.confluence</groupId>
                    <artifactId>confluence-plugins-platform-test-pom</artifactId>
                    <version>${confluence.version}</version>
                    <type>pom</type>
                    <scope>import</scope>
                </dependency>
            </dependencies>
        </dependencyManagement>

Tests to run against Jira in clustered mode.

        Use 'zdu' profile to run tests in mixed mode
        Use 'local' profile to use default versions of Jira for mixed mode
        Use 'debug' profile to enable debugging
        Use 'suspend' profile to suspend tests until debugger has been attached
        Use 'jiradb' profile to fire up database before running tests and stop if after running tests

        Example:
        Running tests in mixed mode with default versions of Jira in Postgres prepared by jiradb:
        mvn -B verify -P zdu,jiradb,local,debug,suspend

        Your local worflow could look like this:
        $ mvn initialize -P jiradb # spin up database and import dump
        $ mvn -B verify -P zdu,local # runs ZDU tests with default configuration

        You can repeat the last step, it'll clean up database without restarting it (which is faster).
        You can stop database by doing:

        $ mvn -B clean -P jiradb #stops database if it exists.

        Once again, you can have full cycle(start database, run tests, stop database) by peforming:
        $ mvn -B verify -P zdu,jiradb,local

        NOTE: jiradb profile doesn't work with Docker Machine - only Docker For Mac or Docker For Windows or native docker
        if you're on linux.

        The wretched refuse of your teeming shore.

        The purpose of this module is to contain code that smells but we have to live with for some time.

        For example JIRA has deprecated methods that we have to call because the alternatives don't do the
        right thing.  So rather than live with all the deprecation warnings looking like broken windows
        we move them into the squalor module abd get them out of our day to day lives.

        Then we we really do see a compiler warning, then its because we are doing something bad and not
        just business as usual.  By removing the 'noise' we can get more compiler 'signal'!

Give me your tired, your poor,
        Your huddled masses yearning to breathe free,
        The wretched refuse of your teeming shore.
        Send these, the homeless, tempest-, deprecated to me,
        I lift my lamp...and will sweep them under the carpet!



        The purpose of this module is to contain code that smells but we have to live with for some time.

        For example JIRA has deprecated methods that we have to call because the alternatives don't do the
        right thing.  So rather than live with all the deprecation warnings looking like broken windows
        we move them into the squalor module abd get them out of our day to day lives.

        Then we we really do see a compiler warning, then its because we are doing something bad and not
        just business as usual.  By removing the 'noise' we can get more compiler 'signal'!
